TY  - JOUR
T1  - Hindsight Bias, Risk Perception, and Investment Performance
AU  - Biais, Bruno
AU  - Weber, Martin
Y1  - 2009/04/23
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1090.1000
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1090.1000
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1018
EP  - 1029
VL  - 55
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Once they have observed information, hindsight-biased agents fail to remember how ignorant they were initially; ?they knew it all along.? We formulate a theoretical model of this bias, providing a foundation for empirical measures and implying that hindsight-biased agents learning about volatility will underestimate it. In an experiment involving 66 students from Mannheim University, we find that hindsight bias reduces volatility estimates. In another experiment, involving 85 investment bankers in London and Frankfurt, we find that more biased agents have lower performance. These findings are robust to differences in location, information, overconfidence, and experience.
AB  - Once they have observed information, hindsight-biased agents fail to remember how ignorant they were initially; ?they knew it all along.? We formulate a theoretical model of this bias, providing a foundation for empirical measures and implying that hindsight-biased agents learning about volatility will underestimate it. In an experiment involving 66 students from Mannheim University, we find that hindsight bias reduces volatility estimates. In another experiment, involving 85 investment bankers in London and Frankfurt, we find that more biased agents have lower performance. These findings are robust to differences in location, information, overconfidence, and experience.
